<exploration xml:id="PA-7-4">
  <p>
    In this preview activity,
    we explore whether certain differential equations are separable or not,
    and then revisit some key ideas from earlier work in integral calculus.
  </p>

  <p>
    <ol label="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        Which of the following differential equations are separable?
        If the equation is separable,
        write the equation in the revised form <m>g(y) \frac{dy}{dt} = h(t)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol label="i.">
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dt} = -3y</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dt} = ty - y</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dt} = t + 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dt} = t^2 - y^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Explain why any autonomous differential equation is guaranteed to be separable.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Why do we include the term
        <q><m>+C</m></q> in the expression
        <me>
          \int x~dx =
          \frac{x^2}{2} + C?
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Suppose we know that a certain function <m>f</m> satisfies the equation
        <me>
          \int f'(x)~dx = \int x~dx
        </me>.
        What can you conclude about <m>f</m>?
      </p>
    </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
</exploration>

